HEADWORD: Incarcerate
<hw>In*car"cer*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Incarcerated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Incarcerating</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + L.
<ets>carceratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>carcerare</ets> to imprison, fr.
<ets>carcer</ets> prison.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To imprison; to confine in a jail or
prison.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To confine; to shut up or inclose; to hem
in.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Incarcerated hernia</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>,
<cd>hernia in which the constriction can not be easily
reduced.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>incarcerated</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>incarcerate</ent>⟦br⟧
